	<div id="comment_top_64604923" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64604923" name="comment_link_64604923" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23378861&amp;cid=64604923" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64604923)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64604923" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64604923); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~MacMann">MacMann</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~MacMann">( 7518492 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64604923"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64604923"><p><div class="quote"><p>You end up with the exact same greenhouse gas you started with, only you used it for a while to store energy.</p></div><p>Hmm, my sarcasm detector picked up a hint of sarcasm.  False positive perhaps?</p><p>Right, this doesn't lower CO2, kind of like a battery.  Or pumped hydro storage.  They also allow us to store energy for a while only to end up with the exact same greenhouse gas we started with.  The lower CO2 comes from maximizing the utility of lower CO2 energy sources, sources that are often intermittent while demand is more constant.  To get the two to play nice we need storage in the middle somewhere.</p><p>I see as an additional b<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64604923">

